Wells, John. 1990. Longman pronunciation dictionary. Harlow: Longman, ISBN 0582053838. This pronunciation no doubt arose by analogy with such words as toll and polka, or because many General American speakers lack vowels of the [&lt;U+0252&gt;] and [&lt;U+0254&gt;&lt;U+02D0&gt;] types; thus this becomes the closest possible approximation to the Received Pronunciation in their phonologies.↩
