John Yatt, The Guardian (2 December 2002), writes: &quot;White men are good, 'dark' men are bad, orcs are worst of all.&quot; (Other critics such as Tom Shippey and Michael D.C. Drout disagree with such clear-cut generalizations of Tolkien's &quot;white&quot; and &quot;dark&quot; men into good and bad.) Tolkien's works have also been embraced by self-admitted racists such as the British National Party.↩
